Sinclair Broadcast Group Inc. is a television broadcasting company that owns and operates, programs or provides sales services to 58 television stations in 36 markets. Sinclair's television group includes 19 FOX, 17 MyTV, 10 ABC, nine CW, two CBS affiliates… MoreSinclair Broadcast Group Inc. is a television broadcasting company that owns and operates, programs or provides sales services to 58 television stations in 36 markets. Sinclair's television group includes 19 FOX, 17 MyTV, 10 ABC, nine CW, two CBS affiliates and one NBC affiliate. The company reaches approximately 22 percent of all U.S. television households. Sinclair acquired Fisher Communications in August, 2013.

Sinclair's current technological priorities are the continued HD upgrades of newscasts in its local markets and the development of mobile applications. 

On May 8, 2017, Sinclair Broadcast Group announced it will be acquiring Tribune Media in a cash and stock deal valued at $3.9 billion. Sinclair will pay $43.50 a share for Tribune Media and will assume approximately $2.7 billion in net debt. The combined company would own 233 television stations in 108 markets, pending any required divestitures by the FCC. Sinclair's president and CEO, Chris Ripley's vision for the combined company includes station- and corporate-level expense reductions, the sale of remaining Tribune Media real estate properties, and the scaling back of "high-cost" original programming on WGN America, undoing a signature initiative under former CEO Peter Liguori.
 
Sinclair Broadcast Group Inc. is a television broadcasting company that owns and operates, programs or provides sales services to 58 television stations in 36 markets. Sinclair's television group includes 19 FOX, 17 MyTV, 10 ABC, nine CW, two CBS affiliates… MoreSinclair Broadcast Group Inc. is a television broadcasting company that owns and operates, programs or provides sales services to 58 television stations in 36 markets. Sinclair's television group includes 19 FOX, 17 MyTV, 10 ABC, nine CW, two CBS affiliates and one NBC affiliate. The company reaches approximately 22 percent of all U.S. television households.

Sinclair's current technological priorities are the continued HD upgrades of newscasts in its local markets and the development of mobile applications.

The MIS Director makes the IT purchasing and hiring decisions for all office locations from the company's Maryland headquarters. The IT Manager collaborates with the MIS Director on system upgrades, implementing software applications and troubleshooting the network database.

The VP of Operations and Engineering has senior decision making authority, but relies on the MIS Director to make most IT department-related decisions. The Manager of Data Systems oversees database operations and security systems while a team of network engineers manages telecommunication technologies.

The Director of Advanced Technology directs system implementation projects, assesses the technologies employed by each of Sinclair's broadcasting locations, and makes purchasing and budget decisions relating to the enhancement of the company's technology architecture.

Some of the stations owned by Sinclair Broadcast Group maintain a small staff of IT professionals on hand who report to the top decision-makers at the Maryland headquarters.





